segments.text: Full-time center managers.
And they had their respective areas that they were out constantly seeing what we could do.
Need study.
And then the divisions, so we wouldn't have any conflict with the divisions, they signed their staff to that center.
And those staff didn't report it to their head of the division.
Didn't report to the city manager.
The center manager had no administrative control over any of the people.
All his was from facilities, providing need studies, making sure the door was open when they spoke to me and so forth and so on.
And that was probably the greatest thing we did during my tenure.
We created those centers.
We were much more cost-effective in delivering our services.
We had availability of lots of good professional help.
You know, you might just need a lawyer for a two-hour presentation here pertaining to accident investigation or whatever.
But we had those available parts in these centers because it's all located in major areas.
And that was probably one of the
the best decisions that I made there at that time.
Not only for the engineering convention center, but for the entire university system.
Because we give them another, another organization represented in this grand system.
And they were always first class operations.
There was no piggyback.
They were always first class.
And when we started to offer the
rig training, all-field rig training, and see the independent drillers come to me and say, well, we've got, this is about 12, 13 years ago, back in 1980.
We need some trained rig workers.
So I said, well, here's what you're going to take.
And I said, we have to have a rig.
We have to have it.
And the independent drillers, so they can give us rig to train on.
They give us the, they underwrote the program, which was rather expensive.
Billy Mack's kid went through it.
and said it was the greatest training he ever had in his life.
But we believed on hands-on training.
We believed in theory, but we believed on hands-on training.
And so that was a great success.
It got us a lot of publicity with the legislature.
Bill Clements came out.
He was governor.
I don't even remember where to go.
The city of Abilene was giving a big barbecue for our facilities.
And he invited them to make an avenue.
Looking back on those 19 years, is there any area of service?
I don't mean geographic area, but any topic that you wish you all could have done more?
Were you frustrated that you couldn't have served this or this or this industry?
No, we couldn't serve them.
We had no boundaries.
See, the Engineering Extension Service is the only agency in the state of Texas that has a statewide mandate to provide probation and technical training on an extension basis.
We had no condominium.
We saw something like you mentioned.
Yeah, we saw it, but we got on it.
We jumped on it right away.
And normally, in all those cases, there's some agency, some trade association or something.
you know, that affected me growing as far as the money raising.
What were your favorite groups to work with?
There must have been some that were more pleasant than others, though.
I don't know.
I was pretty close to the telephone association.
I was pretty close to the romantic co-ops.
I was pretty close to the fire people throughout the state of Texas.
Who were the key state officials that you worked with?
Was that 19 years?
No, but you can name your favorites.
The ones that you would say thank you to.
I guess the one that probably was my favorite, and I don't know why I say that.
But anyway, I like Mark White.
Mark White and I did Gil Reynolds.
See, Joe Reynolds, Reynolds and White was in the law practice together, and then White was his junior member.
And then when he made Secretary of State, because I knew White when he was only with Reynolds in his law firm.
And Mark White, Secretary of State, come on up and run for governor.
I thought that he's the only governor I really, really knew, you know, for any reason.
I mean, I've known all the governors, but I mean, to really know them.
So I guess that's one reason I felt the closest to him.
Bill Preston helped me out an awful lot.
Any time I wanted a appointment with any senator or representative, I could call Bill.
He'd hand me a formal.
This was while he was?
State chairman.
Well, while he was a representative and as he served, you know, he served as chairman of the State House Appropriation Committee for about 10 or 12 years.
Whenever I was in a department with any senator or House of Representatives, I'd call Bill.
He'd have it fun.

Of course, Bill Moore, when he was in the Senate, I'd done a lot of other work for Bill Moore on his outside, and he had that back of A&M on him, the chart for that back of A&M, and he'd talk to everybody about that.
Can you give me an example of lobbying at work where you called somebody and they made the wheels turn?
Describe.
For a specific project?
If there was one.
You can think of them?
Yeah.
I can think of one in five.
There was a big push to create
two or three more fire fields in the state of Texas, and they didn't want to be a part of A&M.
They wanted to create their own, take a bunch of volunteer fire departments.
They thought, you know, they should have their own fire field.
No way in the world it could ever support that.
But still, volunteer fire departments carry a lot of rank in rural areas, which would let you represent them.
And so they put on a push to create a fire field somewhere out in Woodlands area.
Now this was long before the Woodlands was built.
And they bypassed us completely.
And I got a call one day from a member of the representative name down in that area.
He said, what did I think about the, whatever, the Brazoria County that was pushing so hard.
I think the Brazoria County was pushing so hard.
I'm going to tie in with Harris County.
I said, well, it's a very expensive training program.
I said, it's not cheap.
I said, you've got to have good training.
You've got to be damn careful.
And I said, true, the fuel's expensive, and you've got to burn.
You can't just light a match and say, here, now we're going to go put it out.
I said, if you're going to have any fire training or those types of training, you've got to have hands-on training.
They've got to smell the heat and feel the heat.
But anyway, so...
He said, well, they're putting this consortium together now.
He said, I know that they're going to be coming to this for appropriation.
And so we got that stopped.
Now, the way I stopped it, I went down to the organizer, and I said, tell me, what do you guys want?
What do you want?
Tell me what you want.
Give me an opportunity to say no.
So finally, what their big gripe was, is volunteer fire department, they didn't have anybody to place the train on Saturday.
They opened the damn fire to you on Saturday morning.
And that was their big gripe.
You know, they worked five days a week, and they didn't have anybody to place the... Come on, it was too expensive to spend the nights and so forth.
So I said, what's the problem?
What time do you want it?
You want it to open at 10 on Saturday?
Burn it till 6.
You know?
But we killed that one.
But another, at the same time, they were trying to get one out in West Texas.
So...
And the word got to them then what we did.
Then they used the excuse that we live too far away.
We can't come that distance.
All right, can you give an example of where you needed some help in the legislature?
You needed to get a bill passed or some funding and give an example of where some people stepped up and helped the extension service.
No, I'll request one.
state appropriated money.
The only state appropriated money, the way I used my state appropriated money was for the volunteer fire departments in the rural water district.
See, the rest of this is three million dollars.
They didn't support our programs like the PAR and the great television.
No, we never, I don't ever, I didn't, I presented my, I worked with the LBP.
I had the LVB over two months before anybody else did, and I was taking two of them.
But I had programs that the legislature couldn't fuss about.
Volunteer Fire Department, you know, rural water districts.
They couldn't fuss if there was a problem.
And it was, you know, even though we had a $39 million budget, it was only costing the state $3 million.
And we didn't even have any in-house fights with the board or other agencies.
In fact, I had
on numerous occasions challenged Ag Extension Service to get their money the way I got mine.
And John Dutch said one time that Bill Moore and, I don't know, four or five others, along with at that time, I don't know who was the chancellor of the system, I guess it was Dr. .
But anyway, he had them all.
And his main complaint was that he couldn't compete with us.
He had a different clientele.

you know my comeback would tell me a poor group all right now uh you reported to benson and calhoun under dr williams when you were first all right dr williams has uh the heart attack and then the system is recreated the the chancellor of the system recreated in 76
And Jarvis Miller becomes president.
And Ludeke went in and served for Williams.
Right.
And tell them about working with General Ludeke.
No problem.
He and I, he was a general and I was a colonel, so I had to say yes or no to do it.
I didn't argue with him.
How long did it take him to make up his mind about something?
Well, when they told me I was going to move, that they were going to move the headquarters over to Henderson Hall,
At that time Fred told me that this is temporary.
And Dr. Williams told me this is temporary.
But they've all agreed with me that we had to get out of there.
It was that.
It was ISO for the university.
And that's the approach I took.
It's not for me.
It's, you know... Now this is from that, down at the south... Vistasol, yeah.
So Ludeke was in command when they were going to let the contract for Henderson Hall be fixed up.
And...
When I went down there to see the plants, they had my reproduction shop up on the third floor.
And I always had my own reproduction facility.
You may say that's your home.
I admit it's probably your home.
But industrial economics, I had my own reproduction facility.
So I could control the time.
I could move my projects around any way I wanted to.
So I had to deliver them.
But I had a reproduction shop from day one that a lot of people managed.
Now, this was for printing materials?
Yeah.
All the artistic work.
Because all of mine was sponsored research.
And, you know, when I brought down and I had Exxon, I had contracts for Exxon for seven or eight straight years.
And you made it to their board.
Well, they expected a first class presentation.
They didn't want to see some carbon paper stuck out.
So, I mean, I had, that was quality.
That was, and that was built into the price to operate that thing.
That was built into the price.
But anyway,
When I went down to see him down at the General Ludwig was in charge at that time.
I said, you know, we can't have that reproduction facility on the third floor.
I said, well, I've only got one little bitty elevator.
And I said, will there be stuff coming up and down?
And of course, I'd gone into really developing good lesson plans, good technical manuals.
And we had quite a reproduction shop still do that.
And they built that building.
And by the way, we even paid for our building.
We built that $250,000 building out at Annex.
We built that $500,000 Fred Benson, he put $500,000 out of the engine extension.
We built that bomb building.
We built that.
It has its materials.
I built that out of my fee.
I asked him whether it was right or wrong.
I operated the engine extension service, if you will, private business.
I charged for everything.
There was no
I mean, it was all built into the price.
And so we were able to do these kind of things.
But anyway, we got that to General Lukey's locality.
I said, well, let's put it down on the first floor so people can get in and get out.
And we moved that down.
Well, that caused, who'd had that before?
Whoever had that chopper, he wanted to do it.
And General Lukey, out on the phone, said, right from his office.
Who was that guy that had that?
Damn, I don't remember.
All right, then when General Ludeke steps aside, then Frank, let's see.
That's when Jarvis comes in.
Jarvis is president.
and Dr. Williams is here for another couple of years.
How did your reporting process change then?
To whom did you report?
Well, they made Benson vice president of engineering, so I still reported up to him for that.
Okay.
They didn't have, I guess I reported directly to Jarvis to continue educating, because I know I never did go up through Prescott.
Okay.
To my knowledge, that didn't happen.
But now, you know, I'd give them a continuing education after five years.
You know, I only took that job for five years.
So after five years, I was out of continuing education.
And that fifth year come up just about the time Jarvis took over.
Okay.
Right.
So you then, by and large, reported to the system, not through the president's office.
Well, I can't say that because I had to make a budget presentation one year to Jarvis.
Okay.
All right, when he would have a staff meeting of his key people, did you meet with them?
All right, did Dr. Williams, when he gathered the agencies, you met with them when he was chancellor?
Well, one or two meetings we had, yes.
All right, then when he left, Frank Hubert became the chancellor.
Did the routine change at all?
Okay.
See, he was a Fred Benson man.
You knew that.
Frank Hubert.
The first thing he told me, the first thing he did when he became chancellor, he phrased Fred Benson as hell.
He liked Fred.
I mean, Fred and Dean Hubert.
I think they was family.
All right.
Then take me on up through the 80s.
Were there any changes in the routine with different presidents and different chancellors?
Well, of course, Richardson took over in 84.
All right, no matter.
Wait, we skipped the man from Purdue.
No, Hanson.
Hanson.
He was chancellor.
Well, it was about 84 when he did it.
Oh, and Richardson became dean of engineering?
Oh, I'm sorry.
Yeah, yeah.
He became dean of engineering.
All right.
And he was also vice chancellor.
Describe his management style.
No comment.
Was it, it was less direct than Benson and Calhoun had been?
Herb never, the whole time that he was there, maybe before the time I left, Herb never said a crossword.
Herb and I got along superbly.
I can't say enough good things about Herb Richardson from where I come from.
He never objected to a thing I wanted to do.
He approved everything I sent down there.
I met with him once a month.
And there was no problem.
Where Herb's problems was caused by his dad, Jack Flipsey, Ken, what was his name?
Ken Hall.
And we only had one conflict.
Now, you've got to realize I'm a very organized person.
I believe in an organizational chart.
I believe it, and I follow it.
But anyway, you want me to put this on tape?
Let me cut it off.
Let me just talk a little bit.
As you look back, you served 19 years under a number of different presidents and chancellors.
I'm not going to ask the negative, but in the positive, to which ones would you give the highest?
As many as you want to.
Which ones deserve the highest credit?
Doing that 19-year period?
Of course.
I'd have to say Dr. Liggins would take number one.
Why?
Well, I just think he is more knowledgeable about the types of programs that the Engineering Potential Services have.
I think if he...
He accepted them on their merit, not as second class.
He never did give me the feeling that we were second class to anybody, or to anybody else.
He always was fair.
He was very easy to talk to.
Who else?
Well, of course, Mr. Benson.
I'm taking him from the top down now.
Mr. Benson and I had such a long-term relationship with each other.
We had it from about 55 to 54, whenever he'd become dean, until he got totally retired.
We even had a good relationship after he retired.
Fred was always to the point, which I like.
Fred had a lot of characters to call.
He always, if you were going to go out of town with him, you'd say you'd pick him up at 7.30.
He was standing out on the porch waiting for you at 7.30.
He'd always ask you if you were going to go to a meeting, whether it be a legislative meeting, Jim, is there anything you want me to say?
He'd always ask me that question.
Is there anything in here that you want me to comment on?
And I always, you know, I think Fred was a very smart individual.
He certainly commanded the
the attention of a lot of people.
When he spoke, a lot of people listened.
And I admired that in him.
So, I'd have to put him off the top, and then of course, the next man was Calhoun.
I always told him a lot about Calhoun.
We had a lot of working relationships together.
But, in my opinion, I'm not saying one was better than the other, but in my opinion, we had completely different types of leadership.
after the middle 80s.
It was completely different from 84.
Did it become more bureaucratic?
Yes, it was strictly bureaucratic.
You didn't feel at ease picking up the phone and calling.
I never did it in the first place, but I always knew that I could if I wanted to talk to Dr. Williams or Calhoun.
I didn't have to worry about Dr. Williams or Calhoun chewing me out for calling Dr. Williams or vice versa.
Mr. Benson, I didn't ever do it.
to my knowledge, but I always felt comfortable in doing such a thing like that.
We were more, in my opinion, we were more professional there.
We respected each other more.
We had a great deal of respect for each other.
And I think that was probably the one ingredient that made those change in that day before the time I retired in 92.
We had a closeness.
I felt to him as my friend, and not only as my boss, but my friend.
All right.
Now, other than your senior partners, whom did you turn to for advice and counsel and input most often?
To my committees.
I had advisory committees in every sector of my Engineering Detention Service program made up of the leaders in their field.
Like the Telephone Association, I'd have top telephone members.
Power company, I had somebody from the power company.
And we had advisory committees.
We had one whole little advisory committee for the engineering attention.
It had one meeting a year.
And I'd call it in various parts of the state.
My other committee members would, you know, just pick up the phone and ask.
And I kept them informed.
If it was on my telephone committee, you got it.
And I didn't delude you with everything, but the things they ought to see, I sent it to them.
But that's who I got help from.
My users.
As you look back, can you think of any decisions you wish that Texas A&M had made that it didn't make?
Well, I think they should have gone forward and carried the $250 million, which would be good.
No, I can't say that because I don't have the background.
All right.
Let's talk about that a minute.
Coeducation.
higher admission requirements, racial integration, broadening the curriculum, non-compulsory core, all those came in the 60s.
Did those affect your effort?
No.
No, they helped my effort.
You'd be surprised as to how many people.
I always traveled with an engine-intensive car.
That was my Roman billboard.
And you'd be surprised at the number of people that stopped me and asked me questions or to give them information.
I never took a trip that I didn't come back to that I didn't have four or five requests for information.
And of course it was less like the U.S., you know.
This girl was effective, you know.
Everybody helped.
The only ones that's hurting it is people who don't want to join the program.
Now you rode to Austin for a number of years to reserve meetings with Earl Rudder.
With Earl, I only went over there about six months with him because I'd always assigned a driver out of my unit to drive for him.
And when I quit that, it's because the last three that I assigned as a driver, they got them in Westport.
Oh, I see.
I see.
But I only filled in there for a period of about six months, I guess.
So, all right.
During those years that you and Mr. Rutter were going to the same meeting then in Austin, describe your relationship with him.
in the reserve?
Well, of course, Mr.
Rudder was a major general and I was a colonel, and so rank-wise we was miles apart, and I respected him.
I always addressed General Rudder as General Rudder.
I never one time let myself down around General Rudder.
I always was reasonably formal.
We never did
What he did was, he was going to his meeting on Monday night.
And, you know, he'd have to be back.
He'd be back by 11.30, 12 o'clock.
Mr. Rutter, Mr. Rutter, normally on the way back, slept.
And he had the ability to go to sleep.
He said, well, what did y'all discuss?
Well, we discussed the military quarter a bit.
We discussed my view, and I had a better view.
We discussed military personnel quite a bit.

The university, the only thing that would come up about the university, you know, he'd ask you some questions that you really had no answer, and you'd say, well, let's just say I don't think he ever asked this question, but you just said these are the types of questions he'd ask.
Well, has making the Corps adoptive of the persons coming to the university, has that had any effect on you?
You know, I'd say, me personally?
He'd say, well, personally and otherwise.
I'd say, no, we're living in a different world.
And, you know, I said, I wouldn't take all the money in the world for my years I spent in the Corps of Cadets.
I said, but that was in 1940.
And I said, I've got two sons.
And I said, they're both in the Corps, but I guarantee you I didn't push them in the Corps.
They went there on their own.
But we never did get into personalities.
We never did with me because, as I say, I was two ranks below him.
I didn't have any relationship with him as him being my boss other than in the military.
Can you share any anecdotes or amusing or interesting things that happened going to or from that involved Mr. Rutter?
No, but did anything ever go wrong?
Did you all ever have a flat or get there late or anything like that?
Well, I got stopped several times for speeding.
Oh, really?
Oh, yeah.
And what would the highway patrol say?
He was taken.
Oh, he gave you, it didn't matter whose car that was?
We were driving a military vehicle.
Mr. Runner liked to get where he was going fast.
I don't know if anybody's ever told you that before.
No, I didn't know that.
Oh, yeah.
He wasn't allergic to pushing the metal to the pedal.
And I don't know how many tickets he got, but with me, I got one.
All right, who paid the tickets?
I gave it to him.
Okay, so you don't know.
You don't know, OK.
I never did ask him.
He always would take the ticket from me.
He took the one ticket from me.
All right, when the highway patrol would stop, did it impress the highway patrol that here was a major general?
Well, that only happened one time with me.
And I doubt if that highway patrol knew a major general.
All right, so he didn't even talk to the person in the back seat.
OK.
I'm just talking about one time, late at night.
Mr.
Rudder, have a sense of humor?
Very good sense of humor.
Can you give me an example of his?
I'll tell you.
I had an infantry battle group, and we always had the Army command to come down when we were going to get canned.
So Mr. Rutter always used my battle group as one to demonstrate and put on their submission.
So one day, we was having this general come down, a 4th Army commander, General Russell.
He said, Kim, I want to do this.
Will you be out here training at 11 o'clock?
Give me a map.
Tell me specifically where you're going to be.
All of these things.
So I said, fine.
I've done this a dozen times.
So we decided to have an interview in a tank.
And I picked out a beautiful valley, and I had a nice row of trees.
And we come right, so I said, okay, we're going to come right down to our tanks.
And so Bowman, Mr. Runner, and the other general go up.
I went up here and reported to him.
And
Oh, he said, oh.
And I said to this gentleman, I said, now there's a lot of wood rattlers here.
And I said, in fact, I said, there's one right by your foot.
He's a little bit shorter than me.
And I said, put your boots on, then we'll talk.
But anyway, we went up to this thing.
By that time, boy, everything was, you know, I mean, I always had the time right there.
They'd unload all the time they needed for attack, you know.
So Mr. .
But anyway, I told this gentleman, I said, sir, I said, there's another rattlesnake that crashed by your foot.
And I just put my foot back in and stopped it.
He said, didn't bite me, did he?
I said, no, sir, he didn't bite you.
So I got into his car.
He said, now, are you sure that rattlesnake didn't bite you?
I said, no, sir, he didn't bite you.
Mr. Russell said, Jim, I'd like to see you at 1 o'clock today tomorrow.
And I thought he was going to get me for telling him about the damn rattlesnake.
He said, goddammit, Colonel.
He said, when I said, made it realistic, he said, I didn't want you to run over us.
I said, well, I said, at that slope.
I said, you know, I said, to make it realistic, we had to come take part of that slope.
He said, I didn't want it that damn close.
As far as you know, when Earl Rudder was president of A&M, to whom did he turn for advice most often?
Whose advice did he listen to most carefully?
You mean from in-house?
Mm-hmm.
I don't know.
I don't know.
All right.
Then you.
It might surprise you, though, if you didn't know.
It might be some instructor down there or something.
You said in-house.
All right, let's go out of the house.
Away from the campus, whose advice did he hear?
Well, he had here to the board's advice.
He had a lot of respect for the board.
Which, who were the key board members during his day?
Well, let's see.
He got out, when did he die, in 59?
Oh, in 70.
In 69?
Okay.
He died in March of 70, is that it?
Sterling Evans, Zachary, Clyde Wells.
Clyde Wells was on it, and Mrs. Wilson from Lubbock was on it.
And I don't know whether Norman Mosier was on it at that time.
I don't either.
And I don't know whether Mr.
